e=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Vertical Integrat=
ors</a></em><span>, I talked about why there won&#8217;t be any more Aggreg=
ators:</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margi=
n: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>The short =
version is that Aggregators had already won the biggest categories that wer=
e susceptible to Aggregators, and that the remaining categories were too sm=
all to support the necessary model: spend a lot upfront, and make it back o=
n small margin dollars over a huge amount of transactions.</em></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>One addition to that hypothesis is that Ag=
gregators worked for categories that were either digital &#8211; and theref=
ore where marginal costs for new supply was practically zero &#8211; or whe=
re supply already existed, like cars or homes. Better allocating those exis=
ting resources was a coordination problem &#8211; an information problem &#=
8211; and therefore susceptible to Aggregators.</em></p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">The more I think about it, the more I think music might prove m=
